LEVEL 2 — Decompression + Binary Handling


Features
-> Decode compressed file
-> Save decompressed output
-> Simulates binary handling


1. Decode compressed file
Convert the compressed binary data back to the original text.
What happens:
-> Read the encoded data (e.g., 01011) from compressed.txt
-> Traverse the Huffman Tree:
   -> 0 → go left
   -> 1 → go right
-> When you reach a leaf node → you found a character
Why is it important:
-> Compression is useless unless you can recover the original data


2. Save decompressed output
Store the decoded (original) text into a file.
What happens:
-> After decoding, write the result into decompressed.txt
Why is it important:
-> Confirms correctness
-> Lets you compare original vs decompressed file


3. Simulates binary handling
You are mimicking how real systems handle binary data.
What happens:
-> You store encoded data as a string like "010101"
-> Treat each character (0/1) as a binary bit
Why it’s called “simulation”:
-> Real systems store bits in binary format (.bin)
-> Your version uses text → easier to implement
